<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>

    <meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html; charset=UTF-8">
  </head>
  <body>
    <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none">
      <font face="Courier New, monospace">Hello &lt;direct manager, app
        owner&gt;, </font>
    </p>
    <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
        face="Courier New, monospace">The
        SOC team was notified via ticket(s): XXX,XXX,XXX regarding a
        potentially vulnerable web application that was being examined
        by
        threat actors. Upon closing the Xth ticket the SOC suggested
        that the
        next steps would be a vulnerability and manual scan of the web
        application in question. </font>
    </p>
    <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
        face="Courier New, monospace">Upon
        investigation within the scan and testing Windows provided by
        your
        team the following has been determined: </font>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">The web application is
            vulnerable to XSS/XST attacks. </font> </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">Attack vectors include the
            search field as well as the URI/URL of the affected page and
            search functionality. </font> </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">Analysts were effective in
            executing multiple benign XSS/XST simulated attacks against
            the web application and, 3 or 3 were successful. </font> </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
        face="Courier New, monospace">Determining
        the scope of the application and it’s accessibility the SOC is
        suggesting that the maintainers of the web application perform
        the
        following actions on the web site for security coding and coding
        best
        practices: </font>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">Field inputs need to be
            sanitized on the server-side (in this case all IIS input
            must be handled on the IIS side internally, not client
            side).</font></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">Any reusable code where this
            web form was maintained, pushed, introduced and or
            documented must also be considered for review to prevent
            future activity.</font></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">The application owners must
            also conform to testing other input fields or, suggest dates
            and times for the SOC to provide a minimally invasive red
            team engagement to determine other parts of the overall web
            application fall victim to similar attack patterns. </font>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">The business should engage
            with a third party penetration testing organization for
            on-going evolution of the security of our web applications
            and how we can better protect them. </font> </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
        face="Courier New, monospace">While
        this is a common attack vector for threat actors, the
        implications
        for how we protect client data, and our image depends on strong
        well
        developed and defensive web applications that meet and exceed
        industry standards of security with web applications. </font>
    </p>
    <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
        face="Courier New, monospace">As
        our early detections have played a vital role in discovering the
        vulnerabilities that are within the provided web application it
        is
        imperative for the business to not only continually monitor but
        also
        take a proactive offensive role in aggressively finding
        adversarial
        tactics before a malicious threat actor can leverage such
        attacks.
        Based on current trends and research, the vulnerable web
        application
        may be responsible for the following attacks if not fixed in a
        timely
        fashion: </font>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">Hosting a reflected malicious
            web application that can be sent out via URL and attacking
            unsuspecting users through our trusted brand, image and
            longstanding excellence. </font> </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">Providing re-directs to
            malicious web application that mimic our web site,
            competitors in order to provide phishing, spread malware or
            attack other systems. </font> </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">Trick our own internal users
            into believing a maliciously hosted reflected web
            application “authentication form” is part of our business
            whereby making our own staff fall victim to a simple and
            preventable attack.</font></p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
        face="Courier New, monospace">As
        provided, the following are some best practices that can be
        utilized
        by the organization in order to limit or, detect offensive
        attacks
        rather quickly: </font>
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">Introduction of a deviated WAF
            if we already do not have one (F5, etc.)</font></p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">Introduction of security
            mindset in the foundational levels of web application
            development </font> </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">Introduction and use of
            filtration on server-side input; use of HTML stripping or,
            escaping. </font> </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
            face="Courier New, monospace">Active blocking if in the
            event an attack threshold is met. </font> </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
        face="Courier New, monospace">The
        SOC will gladly work with your team to assure all goals are met
        and
        that all future testing is validated, remediated and documented
        to
        help evolve our internal security. </font>
    </p>
    <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
        face="Courier New, monospace">Thank
        you, </font>
    </p>
    <p style="font-weight: normal; text-decoration: none"><font
        face="Courier New, monospace">SOC…</font></p>
    <p><br>
    </p>
